result.execSummary:
The defendant Jarrod Mendell Lane was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments, Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments, Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Original Transcript SENTENCING HEARING (23 pages) commencing MARCH 11, 2016  received and filed.
Count one.
Counts two and three.

Defendant Jarrod Mendell Lane in court with attorney Gary Edward Rosenthal.  Defendant Jarrod Mendell Lane in custody.  Erika Frank Motsch appeared on behalf of Owen Piotrowski for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT 1
The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 6 YEARS, consecutive to current sentence, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 3 YEARS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 2
Court ordered defendant to serve 90 DAYS in the House of Correction, which can be served in the Wisconsin State Prison System, concurrent to count 1. 

AS TO COUNT 3
Court ordered defendant to serve 6 MONTHS in the House of Correction, which can be served in the Wisconsin State Prison System, concurrent to count 1. 

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION
-Batterers Intervention program.
-Parenting classes.
-Mental health evaluation, take all prescribed medications.
-AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
-Absolute sobriety.
-Treatment and/or counseling as determined by agent.
-No contact with victim Linda M. unless approved by the agent. Court grants third party contact with the child/children as approved by the agent.
-Obtain/maintain employment.
-Obtain GED/HSED.
-No contact with firearms.
-Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA & DV surcharges to be paid from 25% of prison funds, balance paid during Extended Supervision, failure to pay results in a civil judgment.
-Provide DNA Sample.
-Restitution set at ZERO,

*Court finds defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program AND the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
